UNDIAGNOSED DEATHS, BUFFALO - TAIWAN (02): (YANGMINGSHAN NATIONAL PARK) MALNUTRITION SUSPECTED
**********************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 21 Dec 2020 10:56 PM CST
Source: Focus Taiwan, Central News Agency (CNA) report [edited]
https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202012210026


The initial findings of an investigation into the recent deaths of 25 wild water buffaloes in Yangmingshan National Park in Taipei indicate that the animals were victims of malnutrition, the spokesman for the park headquarters said on Monday [21 Dec 2020].

At a meeting of experts held by the Taipei City Animal Protection Office earlier in the day to discuss the issue, contagious diseases, pesticides, and fences on the mountains were ruled out as causes of death. A "composite environmental factor" was blamed, the spokesman said, noting that the experts agreed according to preliminary indications that the deaths were associated with insufficient nutrition in the food sources of the breeding sites of the wild water buffaloes.

"Some cattle died of long-term malnutrition," Chang said, explaining that while there was an abundance of grasses in the area, they lacked protein and minerals. The water buffaloes could still be malnourished even when they had enough grass to eat, particularly on rainy days when minerals, known as trace elements, were easily washed off, he said.

The experts made their determination based on autopsies of some of the water buffaloes that died. They suggested that park headquarters put salt bricks and dried grass at 2 locations -- the Qingtiangang Grassland and the Dingshan-Shitiling area -- where the animals usually congregate, as an emergency response measure, Chang said. Over the longer term, the headquarters will increase checks of the animals by park rangers and have veterinarians collect samples if anything unusual related to their health is detected, he said.

According to statistics released by the park headquarters in September, there were a total of 94 wild water buffaloes in the national park. As of 20 Dec 2020, 25 had been found dead, headquarters data showed.

[byline: Su Szu-yun, Elizabeth Hsu]

