[If the primary cause of these deaths was a shortage in food quantity/quality, one would not expect a pattern of mass mortality over a short period of time, but instead occurrence of few deaths per time unit for a relatively long period.

Soay sheep in the Saint Kilda archipelago, Scotland, experience multiannual cycles with periodic mass mortalities of up to 50% of the population. The proximate cause of death has been determined to be protein-energy malnutrition associated with harsh winters (nutritional stress), but parasites have been implicated as a key contributing factor. An experimental study showed that the administration of anthelminthic drugs at the time of the population crash considerably reduced mortality, which supported the link between parasites and death. Environmental stress appears to mediate the increase in parasite burdens observed in Soays, interacting with food shortage to influence survival.

A deteriorated condition may trigger vicious circles where host health becomes increasingly impoverished and severe infection generally more likely, which might eventually lead to death, as observed in Soay sheep. There is a clear potential for synergy between infection and condition: poor condition predisposes to host infections, which further reduce condition, and so on (for a review on the subject see https://bibliotecavirtual.unl.edu.ar/publicaciones/index.php/FAVEveterinaria/article/view/5160). It would be interesting to deepen the investigation of this event so that it could be established how the detected nutritional stress interacted with the other elements of the host-stress-parasite interaction. - Mod.PMB

